              "content": "&nbsp;<strong>Abū-al-Ḥasan al-‘Āmirī</strong>&nbsp;(d. 381/992) or, more fully, Abū al-Ḥasan Muḥammad ibn Yūsuf al-‘Āmirī was a brilliant Khorasanian polymath, Scholar of Divinity, Philosopher, and Sufi with Arab roots. Al-‘Āmirī wrote on Logic, Ethics, medicine, psychology, the interpretation of dreams, physics, and biology. He also wrote on comparative religion and consistently sought to find areas of agreement and synthesis between different sects and religions. In Philosophy, al-‘Āmirī followed in the footsteps of&nbsp;Abu Yūsuf Yaʻqūb ibn ʼIsḥāq al-Kindī (d. 259/873), who is sometimes called the “father of Arab philosophy” and whose Philosophy attempted consciously to respect the parameters of Sunnī&nbsp;Orthodoxy. Al-‘Āmirī held that Revealed Prophetic Truth is always superior to discursive Philosophy, although—in fact—the two should never contradict each other. He also was noted for his defense of authentic Sufism as an essential part of Islam. He was an older contemporary and friend of&nbsp;the Philosopher Abū ‘Alī Aḥmad ibn Muḥammad ibn Yaʿqūb ibn Miskawayh (d. 421/1030), who is noted for his exploration of the Principles of Ethics.&nbsp;Al-‘Āmirī lived about fifty years prior to Ibn Sīnā&nbsp;(Latin:&nbsp;<em>Avicenna</em>)&nbsp;(d. 428/1037). Al-‘Āmirī died and was buried in Baghdad.",
