              "content": "&nbsp;<strong>Al-Imām Mālik&nbsp;</strong>(d. 179/796) refers to Mālik ibn Anas ibn Mālik al-Aṣbaḥī al-Ḥumyarī al-Madanī. He was born and raised in Medina and became one of the most prominent authorities in the Islamic&nbsp;<em>Sharī‘a</em>&nbsp;Sciences and Divinity as well as attaining a degree of authority in the science of&nbsp;<em>Ḥadīth</em>, which in later times was only rivaled by the likes of al-Imām al-Bukhārī (d. d. 256/870) and Muslim (d. 261/875). He is the namesake of the Mālikī School of<em>&nbsp;Sharī‘a</em>&nbsp;Jurisprudence, which is also called the School of the People of Medina, since it followed closely the Traditions that had grown up among the Scholars of that city until the time of al-Imām Mālik. He compiled&nbsp;<em>Al-Muwaṭṭa’</em>&nbsp;(The Well-Trodden Path), which is one of the earliest compilations of&nbsp;<em>Ḥadīth</em>&nbsp;in Islam but also contains numerous references to the opinions in the&nbsp;<em>Sharī‘a</em>&nbsp;Sciences of the Companions and Successors. Thus, it may also be called a book of&nbsp;<em>Sharī‘a</em>-based legal proofs, which the all various Sunnī Schools of Islamic Jurisprudence accept as sources, although they interpret them differently according to their respective School methodologies. Al-Imām Mālik died in Medina and is buried there in the Baqī‘ Cemetery, just to the East of the Prophet’s Mosque.",
