              "number": 54,
              "content": "&nbsp;<strong>Sandalfon&nbsp;</strong>(Hebrew:&nbsp;<em>Sandalphôn</em>; Greek:&nbsp;<em>Sandalfôn</em>,&nbsp;<em>Σανδαλφών</em>) is identified in Rabbinical Tradition with Elijah (Arabic: Ilyās), while they associate Metatron—his “co-brother” or “co-worker” with Enoch (Arabic: Idrīs). Metatron and Sandalfon are generally referred to as Angels, but Sandalfon, who is identified with Gabriel, is said to be the Angel who towers over all others. Since Metatron, who is identified with Michael, and Sandalfon (Gabriel)—like Gabriel and Michael—are conceived of as “co-brothers” or “co-workers,” it has been suggested that the words are derived from the Greek<em>&nbsp;syn</em><em>á</em><em>delphos,&nbsp;</em><em>συνάδελφος</em>&nbsp;(co-brother).&nbsp;Sandalphon is one of the highest Angels of Rabbinic Judaism and one of the oldest Angelic figures to appear in Rabbinic Judaic Mysticism, although he is not mentioned in the oldest enumeration of the four or seven Archangels. Sandalfon is a prominent Angel of prayer and is said to “bring” the prayers of Men before the Deity. The prayers of the Children of Israel are under his protection. Sandalfon is placed over Mankind and has a special relation to the Children of Israel, whom he protects and for whom he intercedes like a High Priest. The Jews wandering in the Diaspora are entrusted to his protection. He prays constantly for them to receive mercy. He is also the Spirit that protects the Souls of the dead, and he will intercede for the scattered tribes of Israel on the Last Day. The American poet Henry Wadsworth Longfellow (d. 1299/1882) wrote a poem called “Sandalphon” based on Rabbinc Tradition about “Sandalphon the angel of glory, the angel of prayer.”&nbsp;&nbsp;",
              "sectionId": "meṭāṭrôn-miṭṭaṭrōn-as-divine-angelic-intercessor-pharisaic-rabbinic-parallels-to-philos-concept-of-the-lógos-high-priest"
