            {
              "id": "fn-futility-of-squaring-circles-trinitarian-theology-the-principle-that-whatever-is-distinct-from-real-being-can-only-constitute-non-being-120",
              "number": 120,
              "content": "&nbsp;<strong>Raḥmat-Allāh al-‘Uthmānī&nbsp;</strong>(d. 1308/1891) or Raḥmat-Allāh Kayrānawī al-Hindī was an outstanding Sunnī Muslim Scholar,&nbsp;<em>Muftī</em>, physician, mathematician, and author and a direct descendant of the third Rightly-Guided Caliph,&nbsp;‘Uthmān ibn ‘Affān&nbsp;(d. 36/656).&nbsp;To his credit,&nbsp;Raḥmat-Allāh al-‘Uthmānī took active part in the unsuccessful armed&nbsp;<em>Jih</em><em>ā</em><em>d</em>&nbsp;against British colonial occupation in Greater India from 1273/1857 until 1275/1859, in which the Hindus also took direct part. As a consequence, the British colonialists punished him and his family by confiscating their extensive wealth, property, and estate. They forced al-‘Uthmānī into exile in the Yemen, from which he walked by foot to Mecca to perform the pilgrimage. Raḥmat-Allāh al-‘Uthmānī&nbsp;is noted as the author of the excellent six-volume Arabic-language work&nbsp;<em>Iẓhār al-Ḥaqq</em>&nbsp;(<em>The Truth Revealed</em>), which was written in response to the fallacies and criticisms of Islam common among Christian Missionaries.&nbsp;It was one of the first Muslim Scholarly works to make full use Western Scholarship in order to ascertain the errors and contradictions of the Bible and Trinitarian Dogma.<em>&nbsp;The Truth Revealed</em>&nbsp;was a brilliant and concise summary and refutation of all the standard charges Western Christians had made against Islam, and it became a standard resource among Muslim Scholars after&nbsp;al-‘Uthmānī’s death. The work sprang from his famous debate in 1270/1854&nbsp;in Agra, India with the German Christian Missionary Karl Gottlieb Pfander (d. 1281/1865) of the Church Mission Society, who was regarded in his time as “perhaps the greatest of all missionaries to Mohammedans.”&nbsp;Raḥmat-Allāh al-‘Uthmānī spoke in eloquent Arabic, which was translated by fellow Muslim Scholars into English. Al-‘Uthmānī was familiar with recent European Theological works that undercut Pfander’s arguments, which Pfander himself was not aware of and had not read.",
              "sectionId": "futility-of-squaring-circles-trinitarian-theology-the-principle-that-whatever-is-distinct-from-real-being-can-only-constitute-non-being"
            }
