              "id": "fn-resurrection-ascension-130",
              "number": 130,
              "content": "&nbsp;In the Qur’ān, “affliction (<em>al-balā’</em>), which is referred to in this verse by, “We will try or afflict” you (Arabic:&nbsp;<em>wa Nabl</em><em>ū</em><em>kum</em>),” is comprehensive, and is used for all types of tests and trials—benefits and blessings (<em>al-ni‘am</em>) as well as various forms of punishment (<em>al-‘adhāb</em>), good and evil, right guidance and misguidance, ease and difficulty, health and sickness, wealth and poverty—to the human being is subjected in this world. When God tests His servant with blessings and goodness, the servant must respond with thankfulness. When the test is with hardship and evils, the test requires patience. God says in the Qur’ān:  “And We tried them with good things and with evil things, so that perhaps they might return [to righteousness]” (The Heights, 7:168; see Qur’ān, 2:155, 11:7). God created human beings in this world and the heavens and earth, which are the context of their existence, not just for them to survive and prosper but in order to try them—whatever the means and circumstances of their survival and prosperity may be.&nbsp;<br/><br/>",
              "sectionId": "resurrection-ascension"
